instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].
        The process description you need to analyze and model a process tree for is: '

input: The process starts with hiring an engineer, which either ends the process directly or triggers a review of a proposal by the engineer. Sometimes our engineers review a proposal so that they can design a blueprint afterwards. If the blueprint involves hiring a new engineer than another engineer is hired, and the process could end again or as well trigger the reviewal of a new proposal from the new engineer. If the blueprint does not demand to hire a new engineer than a plan is implemented which always leads to approvement of the budget. This implementing plan and approving budget procedure than leads back to design blueprint from where the process continues as described.
output: process_tree=*_token( 'Hire Engineer', ->_token( 'Review Proposal', *_token( 'Design Blueprint', ->_token( 'Implement Plan', 'Approve Budget' ) ) ) )

input: The process depicts an order of a product, The following work can be repeated over and over. We have two alternatives to choose from: either "prepare an order" or "receive a receipt". Think of this as a sales workflow where customers can either place a new order (prepare order) or receive a confirmation of their existing order (order receipt). Following, processing starts for an order (either new or existing). This might involve data collection and is followed by generating a report to retrieve customer information, product details, shipping addresses, and so on. We generate a report or output based on the collected data. When the report is generated, the entire flow starts again with preparing an order or ordering a receipt. The process can only stop after either an order is prepared or a receipt is ordered.
output: process_tree=*_token( X_token( 'Prepare Order', 'Order Receipt' ), ->_token( 'Processing Start', ->_token( 'Data Collection', 'Report Generation' ) ) )

input: This describes a day of work. I start my day when customers want to order books (Order_books). They ask me about our proposals of books and their prices. That is why I need to review available proposals (Review_proposals) which aims to evaluate and choose the best options. At this point most times the customer buys the book, but sometimes they need some more information. If customers request to have a presentation, then I create one (Create_presentation) where the outline and main content of the book are shown. This step branches into two concurrent sub-tasks: Edit_text to refine the content of my presentation and Finalize_report to complete the documentation, ensuring a thorough and well-organized workflow from gathering information to finalizing deliverables. The report will be edited until it is perfect. According to the final report, the proposals will be again reviewed. The process is iterated until the proposals are carefully reviewed.

This process begins with the Process Customer Order, handling the initial stages of an order. On Friday the work ends here. On other days, it then moves to Verify Product Availability, ensuring that the requested items are in stock. Afterwards the customers orders are again processed or followed by 2 branches. Besides preparing shipping, workers also Process Order, completing the order procedures, and then Ship Package, ensuring the package is sent to the customer. instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].

        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another.

        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description.

input:
Use Case: Product development

The process is about designing and developing a new product, which involves prototyping, algorithm development, data evaluation, experimentation, reporting, and material preparation. 
Design Prototype is concurrent to all later activities, initiating the creation of a preliminary model. In operation, the process offers three options: Develop Algorithm, focusing on creating computational methods, Evaluate Data, which involves analyzing collected data, and Conduct Experiment for testing hypotheses. After all of these steps are finished the process can end. But if a report is required, then Finalize Report is conducted, where findings are compiled, followed by Prepare Materials, ensuring all necessary documentation and resources are ready. This then repeats the process if new criteria are updated until the design prototype is done, the data is analyzed and experiment is conducted.

Use case: E-commerce case, Inventory control
The process starts with two separate processes which both need to finish. First someone has to Confirm the Shipment Details, ensuring that all logistics information is accurate and up to date. Concurrently, someone handles the inventory report, which provides a detailed account of available stock. Following these steps, he passes a list of Ordered Goods to other team members, where new items are requested from suppliers. This is followed by processing the Customer Payment, ensuring that payment transactions are completed successfully. The payment controller completes this task. While this is happening workers package the items, which involves preparing the product for delivery, and label the package if it is necessary, ensuring the package is correctly addressed and ready for shipment. The workers have continuously package items and label packages and end up their daily work at the end of the day or when the orders are out of stock.

        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.

        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed.

Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities.

instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities.

input:
Use Case: Product delivery
At this website the customer can check their packages which will get delivered or he can order a new delivery. When the customer wants to order a new delivery, the order gets verified with the information given by the customer. At the same time the payment is processed, and an invoice is sent. This step leads to preparing two parallel tasks: Prepare Shipment for dispatching the order and Receive Return for handling any returned items. When this process is finished as well as the verification of the order the process is finished. Alternatively, the customer can track their package. This involves the tracking of the package and the notification of the customer at the same time. Therefore the staff needs to Track Package to monitor the shipment's status and Notify Customer at the same time to keep them informed.

Use Case: Project meeting

This process begins with a Oversee Project Meeting, ensuring that the meeting is effectively planned and coordinated. It then progresses to two parallel tasks: Hold Project Meeting to facilitate discussion and Conduct Team Review to evaluate team performance. Following these activities, it transitions to Review Reports, focusing on analyzing and assessing report details. The process usually ends here but sometimes also a detailed review of Report Content is necessary, ensuring accuracy and completeness, then reports are reviewed again with edited contents. After reviewing report content, process is followed by two alternatives: Review Report Format to ensure proper formatting or Submit Report, finalizing the process. Afterward, the report content is reviewed again.

Use Case: Conducting a Research Study with Stakeholder Feedback
First off in the day we have a meeting to review our progress, that repeats at the end of the day. After that I either work on my study or sometimes I work on its presentation. Working on my study contains to assign my tasks and conduct the research study, if I find new data I will analyze it and then continue with my study. When this is finished, I continue with another meeting to review my new findings. If I work on a new presentation I try to gather all information of my study and I try to make it presentable. input:
Use Case: Report for Client
As a consultant, the daily work is to show our client the new information we gathered. This contains two separate tasks, the preparation of a report and the creation of a presentation. If our customer is happy with our work this is all we need to do. But if he is not happy, we need to do more. We then have two options. Then we rerun the whole process. The second option is to send a follow up email to our customers to organize a new meeting for a solution, offering a choice between scheduling a meeting with stakeholder to facilitate discussions or to follow up on our open tickets to address pending issues and work out their problems with our work. Both options continue with a rerun of the process until our customer is satisfied with our work.

Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.

        You are an expert in process modeling, especially by using process trees and you can generate process trees based on process descriptions. 
        Given a process description between <description> and </description>, identify activities and identify the control flow in which the activities are performed. Then generate a process tree based on the identified activities and use the defined operators to model the control flow. Respond with the generated process tree between <processtree> and </processtree>.
 INPUT: Generate a Process tree based on this process description: <description> Start your day always by sending all packages first and then processing the collected returns from the day before. When you are done with all packages, verify the quality of new products that the manager shows to you, sometimes you will need to store all relevant data to a database and verify the product quality for different conditions. On a busy day your work already ends with these tasks. However, if you have time then prepare orders and help team A by managing some of their customers. In this case do what you would do for your own customers, i.e. first send packages and then process the returns before doing the product quality verifications and storage of data when necessary. In other cases when you have time and team A does not need assistance get some new stock and create invoices for team B. </description>

instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].
        The process description you need to analyze and model a process tree for is: '

input: This process involves designing a system with several alternative and sequential tasks. It begins with Design System and directly complete the process. Besides, the process provides two alternatives to start: Define Requirements to outline system needs or Conduct User Testing to gather user insights. Next, it offers a choice between Develop Prototype or a nested sequence, then process can be completed. In the nested sequence, Enlist Stakeholder Feedback gathers input from key stakeholders. This is followed by Finalize Product Specs, specifying the system details, leading to Harmonize Design Elements, ensuring consistency. The final step in this path is to Gather User Feedback to validate the design, creating a flexible and comprehensive approach to system development. The nested sequence from Enlist Stakeholder Feedback to Gather User Feedback continues until the feedback is collected as requested. Then the sequence ends up after enlisting stakeholder feedback.

input:
Use Case: Conducting Event or Recruitment

When a recruitment is requested an invitation for interviews or for events will be sent and simultaneously representatives wait for responses or if the response already happened a form is filled, and a report is getting prepared in unison. After that the process is finished if there is no response or the decision has been done. Alternatively, the recruitment process continues. Either by a meeting or an interview.  If a meeting is chosen a Call Meeting has been done and after that a discussion about the participants is hold. If the Interview is chosen the interview is conducted and if necessary, further data is gathered and another interview has been organized. After both possibilities the process restarts.

input:
Use Case: Book publication

This process represents the publication of a book. In the process, Publish is concurrent to all activities, including setting the overall goal of making content available and end of process. The main process is that writer writes a book, where the main content is created. This can complete the process. If further refinements need to be done, they can be done while the book published and written. Refinements can be the design of chapters while at the same time the chapters are edited. The second refinement is the publishing of the book. This includes the Design of the Header as well as the formatting of the headline if necessary and editing the headline design. This step can be proceeded multiple times until all is ready to be publish. Then it fulfills the process.
output: process_tree=+_token( 'Publish', +_token( 'Write Book', X_token( +_token( 'Design Chapter', 'Edit Chapter' ), ->_token( 'Publish Book', *_token( 'Design Header', *_token( 'Format Headline', 'Headline Design' ) ) ) ) ) )

Use Case: Recruitment Process
During the recruitment process the recruiting team and I always need to prepare a proposal, drafting a comprehensive plan, and then hire candidate at the end. While I do that, the team conducts interviews, gathering important information about new candidates. Or they review the budget to make sure that we have enough budget for new workers. If we find that the budget is limited, we try to either evaluate our options or we finalize our features, while also developing a design or we generate new requirements. After that we continue with our regular work.

Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].

input:
Use Case: Recruitment
When I started my company, I needed people to work for me. So, I decided to interview the first candidate myself. But while the company has grown, I recognized the problem that I wasnt able to do this alone. So, I decided to hire a manager. But shortly after the manager couldnt handle the work either. Also, the workers were not trained well enough. To solve this, we did two things at the same time. First, we found a trainer and trained him to train our workers. After that we secured it that our workers were trained by our trainer. Secondly, we had two options. Either we could hire a committee, which then would evaluate the resumes of our candidates, or we could recruit a recruiter to recruit new recruits. The recruiter would do that by screening the applicants and if necessary, do a group interview and then screen the remaining applicants. This could also make it possible for the recruiter to recruit another recruiter to help with his work. At the end we choose one option but recognized that we could need both options. After we have done that, we hired another manager to manage all the new workers. This kept going until we had all the workers we needed.

input: The process I am going to describe contains several loops. I start with Create Proposal for Marketing Campaign. Following that, I have several options. One is to continue with Develop Sales Strategy, after which the process can end. If it does not end, I follow with Conduct Market Research. After this, I can continue either with Analyze Results, going back to Conduct market Research, which is the first loop. Or after Conduct Market Research, I can instead go back to Develop Sales Strategy, which is the second loop. After Create Proposal for Marketing Campaign I could instead of Developing Sales Strategy go a different route, and either get at Review and Approval by Manager, immediately followed by either Collaborate on Sales Strategy or Finalize Sales Strategy. Or, instead of going to my Manager, I can create a Marketing Campaign. After any of these outcomes (Sales Strategies or Marketing Campaign), it is back to Creating a Proposal for Marketing Campaign, which is the third loop in the process. The process only ever ends after Develop Sales Strategy.
output: process_tree=->_token( *_token( 'Create Proposal For Marketing Campaign', X_token( 'Marketing Campaign', ->_token( 'Review And Approval By Manager', X_token( 'Finalize Sales Strategy', 'Collaborate On Sales Strategy' ) ) ) ), *_token( 'Develop Sales Strategy', *_token( 'Conduct Market Research', 'Analyze Results' ) ) )

 INPUT: Generate a Process tree based on this process description: <description> For this process, two streams of work happen in parallel. For the first one, a choice must be made between creating a report and generating a summary as well as delivering a package. When either the report or the summary and the package are done, this part is finished. At the same time, complaints need to be handled. More often than not, this comes repeatedly, with booking flights in-between. The second stream of work is either processing a claim or one of two: order a package or pay an invoice. instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].
        The process description you need to analyze and model a process tree for is: '

input: Sometimes the organization just creates a report and then the process is already finished. In other instances, the organization reviews a document and then prepares a research proposal. The proposal then is finalized by analyzing findings or gathering additional data to be presented. However, sometimes additional information is needed. In this case, a meeting with the professor is scheduled as well as a video call with the project partner is hold. The meeting with the professor and the project partners are independent from each other. Also, a decision must be made about inviting more collaborators with expertise or simply conduct a brainstorming session to gather ideas from the people already involved in the proposal. If additional information is gathered in this way, then the process is kicked off again, i.e. either a report is created, or the new document is reviewed etc.

input: The starting of the process involves ordering a package, which is commonly done as the only task of the entire process. However, the full process contains several more steps that are also commonly executed. The process involves reviewing invoices after ordering packages, then creating a quote where terms need to be included. The creation of quotes and inclusion of terms can be done again and again until the final quote is created where then a decision is made between offering the customer to use a discount or to choose payment method. From here either the process restarts with the order of the package, or a proposal needs to be sent. When a proposal is sent an invoice is reviewed again and it continues as described previously from the review of the invoice or when its urgent, a deadline needs to be meet sometimes this requires gathering requirements on what to achieve. It is possible that several deadlines need to be meet. As soon as a deadline needs to be meet that does not require to gather more requirements, the process restarts with ordering the package.
output: process_tree=*_token( 'Order Package', *_token( ->_token( ->_token( 'Review Invoice', *_token( 'Create Quote', 'Include Terms' ) ), X_token( 'Offer Discount', 'Choose Payment Method' ) ), *_token( 'Send Proposal', *_token( 'Meet Deadline', 'Gather Requirements' ) ) ) )

input: The goal of this process is to enhance an existing software product by adding new features while ensuring compatibility and quality. The process starts by designing a prototype. The prototype can be refined by developing algorithms and integrating new features to the existing software. All the designing, developing and integrating steps are performed several times until finally one group is responsible to analyze improvement results or therefore conduct experiments repeatedly and parallelly another group is responsible for either implementing the changes or testing compatibility. While testing the compatibility errors can get recognized and debugged. After the debug is finished it is possible to fix the bug and then further debug the error until it is solved. When the error is solved the testing of the compatibility is continued until no errors are left and the process is finished after both groups have finished their work.

Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities.

Alternatively, customers can Book Table, where they can Eat Entree (enjoy the food at the restaurant) and simultaneously the staff Deliver Dinner, arranging meal delivery and then Gather Groceries for upcoming days. This process repeats during the opening time of the restaurant.

input:
Use case: Launch new or Update product
Sometimes an old product does not sell well enough. So, we try to update this product or launch a new and better product with a new name. With the demand to launch a new product or to update the product version we have two options. First off, the update of the product always starts with a new design, where the product gets a new look. If the chef is not happy with the new design, the design team needs to conduct research and hire experts to find a better and hopefully final design of the product. But sometimes this can take some more tries. When we decide to build a fully new product the technical team needs to take care of building a prototype, if needed the marketing team needs to gather various feedback and engage stakeholders, so we get a good product. After all this work either by building a new product or a new version we give a proposal to the boss to get budget approved, then all teams need to finalize the design and implement a solution if the budget is not met. This completes the process of generating a new product.

Use Case: e-commerce

The shop either gathers product information or processes the order. When product information is gathered this can already finish the process, but if needed also product returns can be handled, while h is done, and the inventory is updated. After that more product information is gathered. The other option to process the order always includes the confirmation of the details of the order as well as processing the order. This can end the process as well. But the is the option to add additional product information while the order is shipped. While this is happening the order is further processed and we jump back to the order being processed.

        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.

instruction:
Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
        
        Now your task is to analyze a process description to identify activities within the process description and the relationship between the activities within the process description. 
        Then model a process tree that represents the process within the process description. Use the operators defined above to to model the control flow and use one verb and one noun if possible to model the activities. 
        You can reason step by step to analyze the process description and model the process tree. However, in the end finish your response with 'process_tree=[insert the modelled process tree here].
        The process description you need to analyze and model a process tree for is: '

input: With this process, two lines of work commence immediately. The first one consists of contacting the sales team and preparing a meeting followed by setting up the materials. Next, I contact the marketing department. Often, this is where my job ends, but sometimes, I have to create content, before contacting the marketing department again. I might need to take a few turns on this one. The other line of work begins with overseeing work. Either the process ends there (after I have also contacted marketing department), or I must implement features. Then it is either going back to overseeing, or one of developing features or conducting tests. That means going back to implementing features. Only if I finished both lines my work is done.
output: process_tree=+_token( ->_token( +_token( 'Sales Team', ->_token( 'Meeting Preparation', 'Setting Up Materials' ) ), *_token( 'Marketing Department', 'Creating Content' ) ), *_token( 'Overseeing', *_token( 'Implementing Features', X_token( 'Conducting Tests', 'Feature Development' ) ) ) )

Following that, the process gets into File Invoice, then Confirm Shipment, and then back into the beginning of the second subprocess. If it does not go into File Invoice and if Get Order hast been completed, then the whole process can end.

Once these three are done, the next step is Finalize Design, followed by Create Technical Specifications, closing the first half. The second half starts with either Conduct Market Research, or with Develop Marketing Strategy. Conduct Market Research would lead to Analyze Customer Feedback, while after Develop Marketing Strategy comes Create Sales Materials. When either Analyze Customer Feedback or Create Sales Materials is finished, the second half is concluded. When both process halves are finished, the process itself is complete.

Process trees allow us to model processes that comprise a control-flow hierarchy. 
        A process tree is a mathematical tree, where the internal vertices are operators, and leaves are activities. 
        Operators specify how their children, i.e., sub-trees, need to be combined from a control-flow perspective. 
        There are four operators and each operator has two children: 
        The sequence operator -> specifies sequential behavior, e.g., ->(S1, S2) means that first S1 is executed and then S2. 
        The choice operator X specifies a choice, e.g., X(C1, C2) means that either C1 is executed or C2 is executed. 
        The parallel operator + specifies simultaneous behavior or indifferent executing order, e.g., +(P1, P2) means that P1 is executed while P2 is also executed or that P1 and P2 are both executed independently from another. 
        The loop operator * specifies repetitive behaviour, e.g., *(R1, R2) means that after R1 is executed, R2 could be executed. If R2 is executed then R1 has to be executed again. This implies that the loop only can be left after R1 is executed.
